{"parse":{"title":"Opsis","pageid":20782736,"revid":815210385,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><dl><dd><i>See also the suffix <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/-opsis\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:-opsis\">-opsis</a>.</i></dd></dl>\n<p><b>Opsis</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Greek_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ancient Greek language\">Ancient Greek</a>: <span lang=\"grc\">\u1f44\u03c8\u03b9\u03c2</span>) is the Greek word for <a href=\"/wiki/Spectacle\" title=\"Spectacle\">spectacle</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Theatre\" title=\"Theatre\">theatre</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Performance\" title=\"Performance\">performance</a>. Its first use has been traced back to <a href=\"/wiki/Aristotle\" title=\"Aristotle\">Aristotle</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Poetics\" title=\"Poetics\">Poetics</a>.</i> It is now taken up by theatre critics, historians, and theorists to describe the <a href=\"/wiki/Mise_en_sc%C3%A8ne\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mise en sc\u00e8ne\">mise en sc\u00e8ne</a> of a performance or theatrical event.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Origins\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Origins</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Aristotle_and_the_Greeks\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Aristotle and the Greeks</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Contemporary_theatre_theory\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Contemporary theatre theory</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins\">Origins</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opsis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Opsis comes from the <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Greek\" title=\"Ancient Greek\">ancient Greek</a> for \"appearance, sight, view.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-OED_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-OED-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The English word <a href=\"/wiki/Optic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Optic\">optic</a> is derived from this word.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Aristotle_and_the_Greeks\">Aristotle and the Greeks</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opsis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Aristotle and the Greeks\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Aristotle's use of the term opsis, as <a href=\"/wiki/Marvin_Carlson\" title=\"Marvin Carlson\">Marvin Carlson</a> points out, is the \"final element of tragedy,\" but the term \"receive[d] no further consideration\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Carlson_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Carlson-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Aristotle discusses opsis in book 6 of the poetics,<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> but only goes as far as to suggest that \"spectacle has, indeed, an emotional attraction of its own, but, of all the parts, it is the least artistic, and connected least with the art of poetry. For the power of Tragedy, we may be sure, is felt even apart from representation and actors. Besides, the production of spectacular effects depends more on the art of the stage machinist than on that of the poet\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Dukore_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dukore-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Contemporary_theatre_theory\">Contemporary theatre theory</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opsis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Contemporary theatre theory\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2><p>\nIn <i>Theories of the Theatre</i> by Marvin Carlson, the word opsis is replaced with the English equivalent \"spectacle,\" but gives opsis/spectacle as much focus as Aristotle does in the Poetics; however, in <i>Dictionary of the Theatre: Terms, Concepts, and Analysis</i> Opsis is listed in the \"terms\" section, and defined as:</p><blockquote>\n<p>that which is visible, offered to the [gaze], hence its connections with the notions of <i>spectacle</i> and <i>performance</i>. In Aristotle's <i>Poetics, spectacle</i> is one of the six constituent parts of tragedy, but ranks below others considered to be more essential ... The place in theatre history assigned subsequently to the opsis, to what we would now call the [mise-en-scene], determined the mode of transmission and the overall meaning of the performance. <i>Opsis</i> is a spectific feature of the performing arts.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Pavis_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pavis-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>J. Michael Walton, in <i>The Greek Sense of Theatre: Tragedy Reviewed</i>, challenges the traditional assumptions about Ancient Greek theatre. He states that \u201cthe visual aspect of the Greek theatre has for so long taken second place to the spoken word...it is still the common belief that what was said in the Greek tragedies was more important than what was seen.\u201d Walton's thesis suggests that Ancient theatre lacks evidence of original productions, but that the written text, in comparison, is more accessible, and as a result, has caused Ancient theatre critics to relegate spectacle/mise-en-sene/opsis to less important aspects of theatre than the spoken word.\n</p><p>\nRonald W. Vince, suggests that while it may </p><blockquote>\n<p>seem logical simply to recognize <i>opsis</i> as stage spectacle or the <i>mise-en-scene</i> and so include it \u2014 if anywhere \u2014 in the vocabulary of performance theory. But there is implied even in Aristotle's use of the term a possible interpretation which would link <i>opsis</i> with the art of writing plays as well as with the art of staging them.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Vince_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Vince-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opsis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-OED-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-OED_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://dictionary.oed.com\">Oxford English Dictionary</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/morph?l=o%29%2Fyeis&amp;la=greek#lexicon\">\u1f44\u03c8\u03b9\u03c2</a> entry in Liddell-Scott disctionary at the Perseus project</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Carlson-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Carlson_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Carlson, Marvin (1993). <i><span></span></i>Theories of the Theatre: A Historical and Critical Survey from the Greeks to the Present<i><span></span></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8014-8154-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-8014-8154-3\">978-0-8014-8154-3</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Theories+of+the+Theatre%3A+A+Historical+and+Critical+Survey+from+the+Greeks+to+the+Present&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8014-8154-3&amp;rft.au=Carlson%2C+Marvin&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOpsis\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://kennydominican.joyeurs.com/GreekClassics/AristotlePoetics.htm\">Aristotle - Poetics</a>, Translated by S. H. Butcher, with original Greek text</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Dukore-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Dukore_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">DUKORE, Bernard Frank (1974). <i><span></span></i>Dramatic theory and criticism: Greeks to Grotowski<i><span></span></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-03-091152-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-03-091152-1\">978-0-03-091152-1</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Dramatic+theory+and+criticism%3A+Greeks+to+Grotowski&amp;rft.date=1974&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-03-091152-1&amp;rft.au=DUKORE%2C+Bernard+Frank&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOpsis\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Pavis-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Pavis_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Pavis, Patrice, Christine Shantz, Marvin Carlson (1998). <i><span></span></i>Dictionary of the Theatre: Terms, Concepts, and Analysis<i><span></span></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8020-8163-6\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-8020-8163-6\">978-0-8020-8163-6</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Dictionary+of+the+Theatre%3A+Terms%2C+Concepts%2C+and+Analysis&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8020-8163-6&amp;rft.au=Pavis%2C+Patrice%2C+Christine+Shantz%2C+Marvin+Carlson&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOpsis\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span><span class=\"citation-comment\" style=\"display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em\">CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Multiple_names:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list\">link</a>) </span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Vince-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Vince_7-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Vince (1990). <i>Opsis as a Term in Dramatic Theory</i>. <i>Assaph C, no 6</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Opsis+as+a+Term+in+Dramatic+Theory&amp;rft.date=1990&amp;rft.au=Vince&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOpsis\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Opsis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Michael Peter Bolus, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://modernmask.org/issue_iv/modernmask_theatre/opsis.html\"><i>Modern Mask</i></a></li>\n<li>Gregory Michael Sifakis, <i>Aristotle on the Function of Tragic Poetry</i>, Crete University Press, 2001</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2224\nCached time: 20180922013238\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.192 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.234 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 241/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 5707/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 69/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 4959/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.151/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 9.38 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  218.906      1 -total\n 73.98%  161.956      1 Template:Lang-grc\n 24.07%   52.690      1 Template:Reflist\n 17.95%   39.300      4 Template:Cite_book\n  0.74%    1.623      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:20782736-0!canonical and timestamp 20180922013238 and revision id 815210385\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"CS1_maint:_Multiple_names:_authors_list"},{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Articles_containing_Ancient_Greek-lang